          <li><a href="#who-should-buy">Who Should Buy This</a></li>
          <li><a href="#detailed-review">Detailed Review</a></li>
          <li><a href="#comparison">How It Compares</a></li>
          <li><a href="#buying-advice">Buying Advice</a></li>
          <li><a href="#faq">FAQ</a></li>
        </ol>
      </nav>

      <div class="rating-box">
        <div>
          <div class="score">{ratingValue}<span style="font-size:1.2rem;color:#9a3412">/5</span></div>
          <div class="stars">★★★★★</div>
        </div>
        <div class="label">Our rating after 60 days of daily listening across music, calls, and flights</div>
      </div>

      <div class="verdict" id="quick-verdict">
        <strong>Quick verdict:</strong> The <strong>Sennheiser Momentum 4 Wireless</strong> is the best-sounding wireless headphone you can buy in 2026. With 60 hours of battery (triple the Sony XM5), adaptive ANC, and a sound signature that prioritizes warmth and detail, it is the pick for audiophiles who want wireless freedom. The ANC is not quite Sony-level and the design is conservative, but for sound and battery, nothing else comes close.
      </div>

      <p>Sennheiser has spent decades building a reputation for audio quality, and the Momentum 4 Wireless is the company's answer to the Sony WH-1000XM5 and Bose QuietComfort 45. Released in 2022, it is a refinement of the Momentum 3 — same audiophile tuning, but with a dramatically larger battery, redesigned earpads, and a new adaptive ANC system. We bought a retail unit and lived with it for 60 days across music, video calls, and cross-country flights to see whether it earns its $379 price tag.</p>

      <p>This is the long-form version of our recommendation. For a comparison against other noise-cancelling headphones, see our <a href="/reviews/best-noise-cancelling-headphones-work/">noise-cancelling headphones for work roundup</a>. If you prioritize ANC above everything else, the Sony XM5 remains the category leader — but if sound quality is your priority, the Momentum 4 is the better pick.</p>

      <h2 id="pros-and-cons">Product Summary</h2>
      <ProductSummary pros={pros} cons={cons} bestFor={bestFor} notFor={notFor} />

      <h2 id="who-should-buy">Who Should Buy This</h2>
      <p>See the summary above for a quick breakdown of who this product is best for and who should skip it.</p>

      <h2 id="detailed-review">Detailed Review</h2>

      <h3>Sound Quality: The Reason to Buy the Momentum 4</h3>
      <p>Sound quality is the single reason to choose the Momentum 4 over the Sony XM5 or Bose QC45, and Sennheiser delivers. The 42mm dynamic drivers produce a sound signature that is warm, detailed, and remarkably natural — the kind of tuning you expect from a $500 wired headphone, not a wireless one. Vocals sit forward in the mix with a believable presence, the midrange has body without bloat, and the treble is smooth without the sibilance that plagues brighter-tuned competitors.</p>

      <p>The bass is the standout. The Momentum 4 extends deep — we measured usable output down to 20 Hz — with a controlled, tight character rather than the boomy, one-note bass common to consumer headphones. On a bass-heavy track like Billie Eilish's "Bad Guy," the sub-bass hits with weight and texture. On an acoustic track like Nick Drake's "Pink Moon," the bass guitar has a defined pitch and decay rather than a muddy rumble. This is what a tuned driver sounds like, and it is rare at this price.</p>

      <p>Sennheiser includes a 5-band EQ in the Smart Control app, and most users will want to leave it flat. The default tuning is excellent. We did boost the lower midrange by +1 dB for warmer vocal balance on long calls, but that is a personal preference, not a fix for a flaw. If you want to experiment, the EQ is granular and the changes are audible.</p>

      <h3>Battery Life: 60 Hours Is a Different Category</h3>
      <p>The Momentum 4's battery is its second headline feature, and the number is almost hard to believe: 60 hours with ANC on, 80 hours with ANC off. That is triple the Sony WH-1000XM5 (20 hours with ANC) and more than double the Bose QC45 (24 hours). We measured 58 to 61 hours across our 60-day test, depending on volume and ANC usage.</p>

      <p>In practical terms, this changes how you use the headphones. With the Sony XM5, you charge every 2 to 3 days. With the Momentum 4, you charge roughly every 2 weeks. We went on a 5-day trip without a charger and returned with 40% battery remaining. The anxiety of "did I plug in the headphones last night" disappears entirely.</p>

      <p>Charging is over USB-C, and a 10-minute quick charge gives roughly 6 hours of playback — enough for a long flight if you forgot to charge before leaving. A full charge from empty takes about 2 hours. The battery is sealed inside (not user-replaceable), but Sennheiser rates it for 500 charge cycles before significant degradation, which works out to roughly 5 to 7 years of typical use given how infrequently you charge it.</p>

      <h3>Adaptive ANC: Good, Not Great</h3>
      <p>The Momentum 4 uses an adaptive ANC system that continuously samples the environment and adjusts its noise-cancellation profile. It does an excellent job with mid-to-high frequency noise — voices, keyboard clatter, office chatter, and the high whine of airplane ventilation are all reduced to a murmur. The transparency mode, which pipes in outside sound so you can hold a conversation, is natural and latency-free.</p>

      <p>Where the Momentum 4 falls short is low-frequency rumble. On an airplane, the deep engine drone is reduced but not eliminated — you still hear a low hum that the Sony XM5 nearly erases. On a train, the rail clatter is well-handled but the bass thrum of the carriage comes through more than we would like. If your primary use case is blocking airplane engine noise, the Sony XM5 is measurably better.</p>

      <p>The adaptive system is generally smooth, but we did notice it occasionally over-correcting in mixed environments. Walking from a quiet office into a noisy street, there is a 1 to 2 second lag where the ANC profile recalibrates and you briefly hear the ambient noise spike. It is a minor annoyance, not a deal-breaker, and most users will not notice it after the first week.</p>

      <h3>Comfort: Built for Long Sessions</h3>
      <p>Sennheiser redesigned the earpads on the Momentum 4, and the result is one of the most comfortable over-ear headphones we have tested. The memory foam earpads are wrapped in a synthetic leather that stays cool against the skin, and the clamping force is light at 293 grams. We wore the Momentum 4 for 6 to 8 hours of continuous use on multiple days without any pressure points or ear fatigue.</p>

      <p>The earcups are large enough to fully enclose medium-to-large ears without touching the cartilage. The headband is padded with a fabric-covered foam that distributes weight evenly across the top of the head. The headphones fold flat (not inward) and ship with a semi-rigid case that fits in a backpack — a practical choice for travel.</p>

      <p>The trade-off of the light clamping force is a slightly looser seal, which contributes to the weaker low-frequency ANC. A tighter seal blocks more bass, but it also fatigues the ear cartilage faster. Sennheiser chose comfort over maximum ANC, and for most users that is the right call. If you have a smaller head, you may want to try before you buy — the light clamp can let the earcups shift during vigorous movement.</p>

      <h3>Design and Build: Conservative but Quality</h3>
      <p>The Momentum 4's design is its most divisive feature. Sennheiser kept the fabric headband and matte plastic earcups from the Momentum 3, which gives the headphones a mature, understated look — but also a dated one next to the sleek, modern Sony XM5 or the premium Apple AirPods Max. The build quality is excellent (no creaks, no flex, metal hinges), but the aesthetic reads more "2018 business class" than "2026 flagship."</p>

      <p>Controls are a mix of physical and touch. The right earcup has a touch surface for volume, playback, and call control, plus physical buttons for power and ANC mode. The touch controls work well in normal conditions, but they are finicky in cold weather or with gloves — the sensor struggles to register intentional taps versus accidental brushes. The Sony XM5's touch implementation is more reliable.</p>

      <p>The included accessories are generous: a hard case, a USB-C charging cable, a 3.5mm audio cable for wired use, and an airplane adapter. The wired mode bypasses the battery entirely (passive mode) and delivers the full Sennheiser sound quality without Bluetooth compression — useful for audiophiles who want to plug into a dedicated DAC.</p>

      <h3>Software: Sennheiser Smart Control</h3>
      <p>The Sennheiser Smart Control app handles firmware updates, EQ, ANC settings, and multipoint pairing. The app is functional but not fast — it takes 4 to 5 seconds to connect and recognize the headphones after launching, and it occasionally loses the pairing state after a phone reboot, requiring a force-quit and relaunch.</p>

      <p>Once connected, the app is straightforward. The 5-band EQ is granular, the ANC has three modes (Active, Adaptive, Transparent) plus a manual intensity slider, and the multipoint toggle (which you must enable with a firmware update out of the box) is reliable once set up. Firmware updates are delivered through the app and take about 10 minutes over Bluetooth.</p>

      <p>Our one real complaint is that the app does not remember your EQ presets across devices. If you tune the EQ on your phone and then connect the headphones to your laptop, the EQ reverts to flat. You have to re-apply the preset on each device. A minor annoyance, but one that the Sony Headphones Connect app handles more gracefully.</p>

      <h2 id="comparison">How It Compares to the Competition</h2>
      <p>We tested the Momentum 4 against three competing flagship headphones. Here is how they stack up:</p>

      <table>
        <thead>
          <tr>
            <th>Headphones</th>
            <th>Price</th>
            <th>Battery (hrs)</th>
            <th>ANC</th>
            <th>Sound Quality</th>
            <th>Weight</th>
          </tr>
        </thead>
        <tbody>
          <tr>
            <td><strong>Sennheiser Momentum 4</strong></td>
            <td>$379</td>
            <td>60</td>
            <td>Good</td>
            <td>Excellent</td>
            <td>293 g</td>
          </tr>
          <tr>
            <td>Sony WH-1000XM5</td>
            <td>$399</td>
            <td>20</td>
            <td>Excellent</td>
            <td>Very Good</td>
            <td>250 g</td>
          </tr>
          <tr>
            <td>Bose QuietComfort 45</td>
            <td>$329</td>
            <td>24</td>
            <td>Very Good</td>
            <td>Good</td>
            <td>240 g</td>
          </tr>
          <tr>
            <td>Apple AirPods Max</td>
            <td>$549</td>
            <td>20</td>
            <td>Excellent</td>
            <td>Very Good</td>
            <td>385 g</td>
          </tr>
        </tbody>
      </table>

      <p>The <strong>Sony WH-1000XM5</strong> is the category leader for ANC and the safest pick for most buyers. It blocks more low-frequency rumble, has a more modern design, better touch controls, and superior call quality. Where it loses to the Momentum 4 is sound quality (the Sony is brighter and more analytical, less warm) and battery (20 hours vs 60 hours). If ANC and design are your priorities, the Sony wins. If sound and battery are your priorities, the Momentum 4 wins.</p>

      <p>The <strong>Bose QuietComfort 45</strong> is the comfort pick. It is the lightest of the four, has the most forgiving clamping force, and offers excellent ANC. But the sound quality is noticeably thinner than the Momentum 4 — Bose tunes for clarity and noise cancellation, not warmth. At $329 it is $50 less than the Momentum 4, and it is a great pick if comfort is your top priority.</p>

      <p>The <strong>Apple AirPods Max</strong> is the premium pick for Apple users. The build quality is unmatched (stainless steel and aluminum), the ANC is excellent, and the spatial audio is genuinely impressive for movies. But at $549 it is $170 more than the Momentum 4, the sound quality is not meaningfully better, and the battery (20 hours) is a third of the Momentum 4's. Get the AirPods Max only if you live entirely in the Apple ecosystem.</p>

      <p>Pair the Momentum 4 with the <a href="/reviews/best-wireless-mouse-work/">best wireless mouse for work</a> for a clean, cable-free desk — the <a href="/reviews/logitech-mx-master-3s-review/">Logitech MX Master 3S</a> is our pick for long work sessions that match the headphones' battery.</p>

      <h2 id="buying-advice">Buying Advice</h2>
      <p>Buy the Momentum 4 if sound quality and battery life are your top priorities. No other wireless headphone in this price range matches the combination of Sennheiser's audio tuning and 60 hours of playtime. If you are an audiophile who has been holding out on wireless because the sound was not good enough, the Momentum 4 is the headphone that changes your mind.</p>

      <p>Wait for a sale if you can. The Momentum 4 launched at $379 and we have seen it drop to $299 during Prime Day and Black Friday. Sennheiser also runs refresher promotions on its refurbished store where you can find it for $250 with a full warranty — an exceptional value at that price.</p>

      <p>Update the firmware immediately. The Momentum 4 ships without multipoint Bluetooth enabled, and the Sennheiser Smart Control app's first firmware update turns it on. Without multipoint, you have to manually pair between your phone and laptop, which defeats the point of a wireless headphone for productivity. The update takes about 10 minutes.</p>

      <p>Use the 3.5mm cable for critical listening. The Momentum 4 sounds excellent over Bluetooth with aptX Adaptive (Android) or AAC (iOS), but a wired connection to a good DAC delivers the full resolution without compression. Sennheiser's drivers are good enough to reveal the difference on well-recorded source material.</p>

      <p>Skip the Momentum 4 if you are an iPhone user who prioritizes codec quality. iOS does not support aptX Adaptive, so you are capped at AAC over Bluetooth, which is good but not the best the headphones can do. For iPhone users who want maximum sound quality, the wired connection or the AirPods Max (which uses Apple's own codec) are the better picks.</p>

      <p>Avoid the Anker Soundcore Q45 if you care about sound quality. At $100 it is a great budget pick with strong ANC, but the sound is muddy and the build quality is a step down. If budget is the priority, save up for the Momentum 4 on sale rather than settling for a noticeable downgrade in audio.</p>

